WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:03.545
In this lesson, we're focusing on three
closely related inhalation

2
00:00:03.545 --> 00:00:06.164
injuries you will see in critical care and
emergency settings.

3
00:00:06.864 --> 00:00:09.045
Smoke inhalation, thermal lung injury, and

4
00:00:09.045 --> 00:00:10.284
carbon monoxide intoxication.

5
00:00:10.625 --> 00:00:14.505
These conditions often occur together,
especially in patients rescued from

6
00:00:14.505 --> 00:00:14.824
fires.

7
00:00:14.984 --> 00:00:18.045
And your job as an RT is to quickly
recognize what's happening,

8
00:00:18.545 --> 00:00:21.245
what's most dangerous right now, and what
needs to be

9
00:00:21.245 --> 00:00:21.684
treated first.

10
00:00:22.145 --> 00:00:23.704
Let's start with the big picture.

11
00:00:24.584 --> 00:00:27.784
Smoke inhalation introduces toxic
particles and chemicals into the airway.

12
00:00:27.784 --> 00:00:30.745
This leads to airway inflammation,
bronchospasm,

13
00:00:31.045 --> 00:00:31.844
and mucus production.

14
00:00:32.325 --> 00:00:35.505
Very similar to obstructive processes you
already know, but often

15
00:00:35.505 --> 00:00:36.604
more acute and severe.

16
00:00:37.625 --> 00:00:39.685
Thermal injury primarily affects the upper
airway.

17
00:00:40.325 --> 00:00:42.744
Heat causes swelling of the airway
tissues, which can rapidly

18
00:00:42.744 --> 00:00:43.625
progress to obstruction.

19
00:00:44.185 --> 00:00:46.224
This is why early airway assessment is
critical.

20
00:00:46.744 --> 00:00:49.604
If you wait too long, intubation may
become extremely difficult

21
00:00:49.604 --> 00:00:50.325
or impossible.

22
00:00:51.145 --> 00:00:54.145
Now, carbon monoxide intoxication is a
completely different problem.

23
00:00:54.145 --> 00:00:57.424
It's not a ventilation issue, it's an
oxygen transport problem.

24
00:00:58.264 --> 00:01:01.284
Carbon monoxide binds to hemoglobin with a
much higher affinity than oxygen,

25
00:01:01.924 --> 00:01:02.865
forming arboxyhemoglobin.

26
00:01:03.604 --> 00:01:06.044
This prevents oxygen from being delivered
to tissues, even if

27
00:01:06.044 --> 00:01:07.764
the patient's lungs are moving air
normally.

28
00:01:08.105 --> 00:01:09.904
Here's the key RT insight.

29
00:01:10.544 --> 00:01:13.324
Pulse oximetry can look normal in carbon
monoxide poisoning.

30
00:01:13.565 --> 00:01:16.305
So if you rely only on SpO2, you can miss

31
00:01:16.305 --> 00:01:17.625
a life-threatening hypoxia.

32
00:01:17.625 --> 00:01:19.425
Instead, you need to think clinically.

33
00:01:19.985 --> 00:01:22.004
Look for exposure history, symptoms like
headache,

34
00:01:22.305 --> 00:01:24.525
confusion, dizziness, and confirm with CO

35
00:01:24.525 --> 00:01:25.745
oximetry when available.

36
00:01:26.105 --> 00:01:29.385
From a cause-to-effect standpoint, smoke
and toxins,

37
00:01:29.764 --> 00:01:31.864
right-pointing arrow, airway inflammation
and obstruction.

38
00:01:32.964 --> 00:01:34.785
Heat, right-pointing arrow, upper airway

39
00:01:34.785 --> 00:01:35.125
swelling.

40
00:01:36.165 --> 00:01:38.084
Carbon monoxide, right-pointing arrow,
impaired

41
00:01:38.084 --> 00:01:38.845
oxygen delivery.

42
00:01:39.404 --> 00:01:40.964
Now let's talk priorities.

43
00:01:41.364 --> 00:01:42.184
First, airway.

44
00:01:42.705 --> 00:01:44.584
Look for signs like hoarseness, soot,

45
00:01:45.065 --> 00:01:45.885
burns, or stridor.

46
00:01:45.885 --> 00:01:48.705
These are red flags for impending airway
compromise.

47
00:01:49.805 --> 00:01:50.684
Second, oxygenation.

48
00:01:51.044 --> 00:01:54.305
High-flow oxygen is critical, especially
for carbon monoxide poisoning,

49
00:01:54.705 --> 00:01:56.745
because it helps displace CO from
hemoglobin.

50
00:01:57.745 --> 00:01:59.625
Third, ventilation and airway clearance.

51
00:02:00.285 --> 00:02:02.584
Monitor for bronchospasm, secretions, and
worsening

52
00:02:02.584 --> 00:02:03.264
work of breathing.

53
00:02:03.705 --> 00:02:04.944
And finally, escalation.

54
00:02:05.065 --> 00:02:08.065
If the patient shows signs of fatigue,
altered mental status,

55
00:02:08.124 --> 00:02:10.464
or airway compromise, you need to act
quickly.

56
00:02:10.865 --> 00:02:13.404
From a board prep perspective, remember
this.

57
00:02:13.404 --> 00:02:16.464
Normal SpO2 does not rule out CO
poisoning.

58
00:02:17.324 --> 00:02:19.324
Upper airway burns can deteriorate
rapidly.

59
00:02:20.024 --> 00:02:21.725
Early intervention saves airways.

60
00:02:22.425 --> 00:02:24.904
As the RT, your role is to recognize the
pattern,

61
00:02:25.585 --> 00:02:28.585
prioritize airway and oxygen delivery, and
continuously reassess for deterioration.

62
00:02:29.225 --> 00:02:31.744
That's the foundation you'll build on as
we move through this lesson.

